    <details>
        <summary class="dropdown">Current Context</summary>
        <p>
            The current estimate of unhoused persons in California is 187,000 people. 
            In 2023, there were reported 71,000 emergency shelters available, less than half of what it would take to house the current population. 
            A Supreme Court decision within the last year, allows for governments to clear out homeless encampments and police those who are living on the streets. 
            Governor Gavin Newsom said in response to this ruling, &quot;This decision removes the legal ambiguities that have tied the hands of local officials for years and 
            limited their ability to deliver on common-sense measures to protect the safety and well-being of our communities&quot; &#40;Kendall, 2024&#41;. He joins other associations who 
            see this ruling as granting governments the ability to protect citizens who are housed and affected by encampments. Other issues in regards to homelessness include 
            hostile architecture. This architecture aims to prevent people from sleeping in public in front of homes and businesses as well as in public places such as parks. 
            In cities such as San Francisco, this is a major problem. There has been an uptick in large metal planters on the sidewalks preventing people from sleeping on the 
            sidewalks. This architecture arises under beautification projects aimed 
            at neighborhood improvement, but the intended or unintended consequences are preventing the encampments of people who have nowhere else to go.
        </p>
