    <details>
        <summary class="dropdown">What is Hostile Architecture?</summary>
        <p>
            Hostile Architecture is defined as &quot;the design of public spaces in a way that stops unwanted behaviour, for example putting spikes &#40;pieces of metal with a sharp point&#41; 
            in doorways to stop people who have nowhere to live from sleeping there&quot; &#40;Cambridge Dictionary&#41;. 
        </p>
        <img src="/src/components/images/planters3.jpeg" id="BRC">
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary class="dropdown">Historical Efforts to Solve the Problem</summary>
        <p>
            In August of 2024, Governor Gavin Newsom signed two bills to address the homelessness crisis. 
            One bill, AB 2835, aims at making it easier for programs to place unhoused people in motels and hotels for more than 30 days, a 
            program which has proven to provide more stability to those people in search for a better life. The other, AB 3057, streamlines the process for local governments to 
            construct Junior Accessory Dwelling Units which are 500 sq. ft dwellings that are an affordable housing solution. 
        </p>
